on the railroad ♪

1:00:13.776 --> 1:00:16.988
♪ All the live long day ♪

1:00:17.071 --> 1:00:20.158
♪ I've been working
on the railroad ♪

1:00:20.241 --> 1:00:21.993
Lipton:
<i>We took over</i>
<i>100 German prisoners.</i>

1:00:22.076 --> 1:00:24.037
<i>After that</i>
<i>it was mostly clean up.</i>

1:00:25.330 --> 1:00:27.165
Let's go,
move it, move it!

1:00:27.248 --> 1:00:28.458
Take 'em down
to the barn.

1:00:28.541 --> 1:00:32.086
♪ Rise up early
in the morn ♪

1:00:33.546 --> 1:00:34.756
Sit down.

1:00:36.257 --> 1:00:38.343
(gunshots)

1:00:38.426 --> 1:00:40.053
Sniper!

1:00:40.136 --> 1:00:41.387
Take cover,
take cover!

1:00:47.977 --> 1:00:49.145
Come on, come on.

1:00:49.228 --> 1:00:51.731
Where is he?

1:00:53.358 --> 1:00:56.361
Shit, I can't see him.

1:00:58.738 --> 1:01:01.324
Second floor,
building on the right.

1:01:01.407 --> 1:01:03.701
Don't miss, Shifty.

1:01:03.785 --> 1:01:04.869
Now!

1:01:14.754 --> 1:01:16.964
(men cheering)

1:01:17.048 --> 1:01:19.884
All right!

1:01:17.048 --> 1:01:19.884
Yeah!

1:01:25.098 --> 1:01:26.140
Man:
Over here.

1:01:26.224 --> 1:01:27.517
I need help
over here.

1:01:27.600 --> 1:01:29.352
Can you guys help me?

1:01:27.600 --> 1:01:29.352
Medic! I need
a medic over here!

1:01:29.435 --> 1:01:31.646
Lipton:
<i>Mellet, Herron,</i>
<i>Sowosko, and Ken Webb</i>

1:01:31.729 --> 1:01:33.356
<i>were killed</i>
<i>by a sniper.</i>

1:01:33.439 --> 1:01:36.234
<i>There would've been more</i>
<i>if it hadn't been</i>
<i>for Shifty Powers.</i>

1:01:36.317 --> 1:01:37.902
(chattering)

1:01:37.985 --> 1:01:39.779
Sergeant:
...walking wounded
to the aid station.

1:01:39.862 --> 1:01:41.239
Man:
Yes, Sergeant.

1:01:41.322 --> 1:01:44.409
♪ ♪

1:02:00.508 --> 1:02:01.759
You hit bad,
Perconte?

1:02:01.843 --> 1:02:03.094
Beautiful wound, Lip.

1:02:04.345 --> 1:02:05.638
They shot me
right through my ass.

1:02:05.721 --> 1:02:07.140
You hang tough.

1:02:05.721 --> 1:02:07.140
Hey, Sarge.

1:02:07.223 --> 1:02:09.267
Yeah?

1:02:07.223 --> 1:02:09.267
Is it true
about Dike?

1:02:09.350 --> 1:02:10.643
Yeah.

1:02:10.726 --> 1:02:12.645
Thank god
for small mercies, huh?

1:02:13.688 --> 1:02:14.689
Yeah.

1:02:27.660 --> 1:02:29.454
Lipton:
<i>We'd been looking down</i>
<i>at the town of Foy</i>

1:02:29.537 --> 1:02:30.955
<i>for the better part</i>
<i>of a month,</i>

1:02:31.038 --> 1:02:33.040
<i>knowing that's where</i>
<i>we had to go.</i>

1:02:34.083 --> 1:02:36.085
<i>It was a great relief</i>
<i>to have done it.</i>

1:02:38.754 --> 1:02:40.089
<i>I guess a lot</i>
<i>of the men thought</i>

1:02:40.173 --> 1:02:42.008
<i>once we'd taken Foy,</i>
<i>they'd get us off the line,</i>

1:02:42.091 --> 1:02:44.469
<i>ship us back to Mourmelon</i>
<i>for a breather.</i>

1:02:44.552 --> 1:02:46.929
<i>But that</i>
<i>wasn't to be.</i>

1:02:47.013 --> 1:02:48.848
<i>Two days later,</i>
<i>we took Noville,</i>

1:02:48.931 --> 1:02:50.600
<i>and after that,</i>
<i>Rachamps.</i>

1:02:55.104 --> 1:02:58.107
(singing)

1:03:12.663 --> 1:03:15.750
Lipton:
<i>We spent our night</i>
<i>in Rachamps in a convent.</i>

1:03:15.833 --> 1:03:18.669
<i>It was the first time</i>
<i>we'd spent a night indoors</i>
<i>in a month.</i>

1:03:31.599 --> 1:03:34.310
<i>The sisters there brought in</i>
<i>their choir to sing for us.</i>

1:03:34.393 --> 1:03:35.853
<i>It was heaven.</i>

1:03:43.778 --> 1:03:45.863
<i>The mood of the men</i>
<i>was relaxed.</i>

1:03:45.947 --> 1:03:47.114
<i>We were finally</i>
<i>being relieved</i>

1:03:47.198 --> 1:03:48.658
<i>and would soon</i>
<i>be in Mourmelon.</i>

1:03:50.952 --> 1:03:52.245
<i>Of course,</i>
<i>in the morning we found out</i>

1:03:52.328 --> 1:03:53.788
<i>Mourmelon would</i>
<i>have to wait.</i>

1:03:53.871 --> 1:03:55.873
<i>Hitler had launched</i>
<i>a counter-offensive in Alsace,</i>

1:03:55.957 --> 1:03:57.917
<i>and we were bound</i>
<i>for the town of Hagenau</i>

1:03:58.000 --> 1:03:59.335
<i>to help</i>
<i>hold the line.</i>

1:03:59.418 --> 1:04:02.046
<i>But at least for that night</i>
<i>we didn't know it yet.</i>

1:04:02.129 --> 1:04:04.590
<i>That night</i>
<i>we were okay.</i>

1:04:09.262 --> 1:04:11.847
(singing continues)

1:04:23.651 --> 1:04:24.735
<i>I spent part</i>
<i>of that night</i>

1:04:24.819 --> 1:04:25.903
<i>trying to come up</i>
<i>with a roster</i>

1:04:25.987 --> 1:04:28.447
<i>for the company</i>
<i>to see who we had left.</i>

1:04:28.531 --> 1:04:31.242
<i>We'd come into Belgium</i>
<i>with 121 men and officers,</i>

1:04:31.325 --> 1:04:33.202
<i>plus 24 replacements.</i>

1:04:33.286 --> 1:04:35.246
<i>That's 145 total.</i>

1:04:35.329 --> 1:04:37.748
<i>We were going out</i>
<i>with 63.</i>

1:04:39.917 --> 1:04:42.878
<i>Guarnere was badly wounded</i>
<i>and Hoobler died accidentally.</i>

1:04:47.258 --> 1:04:49.218
<i>Joe Toye had</i>
<i>lost his leg.</i>

1:04:55.850 --> 1:04:58.019
<i>Among the dead</i>
<i>were Herron, Mellet,</i>

1:04:58.102 --> 1:05:01.272
<i>Sowosko, Kenneth Webb,</i>
<i>Harold Webb,</i>

1:05:01.355 --> 1:05:03.441
<i>Alex Penkala,</i>
<i>and Skip Muck.</i>

1:05:07.695 --> 1:05:09.989
<i>Our month in Belgium</i>
<i>cost us one good officer,</i>

1:05:10.072 --> 1:05:11.157
<i>Buck Compton,</i>

1:05:11.240 --> 1:05:12.700
<i>and one bad one,</i>

1:05:12.783 --> 1:05:13.909
<i>Norman Dike.</i>

1:05:19.206 --> 1:05:20.833
<i>But we gained</i>
<i>a good one in the end,</i>

1:05:20.916 --> 1:05:23.085
<i>so I guess</i>
<i>we came out ahead.</i>

1:05:33.929 --> 1:05:35.264
(clearing throat)

1:05:33.929 --> 1:05:35.264
What is it?

1:05:36.432 --> 1:05:37.642
Nothing.

1:05:39.977 --> 1:05:41.687
Well, I'd better
get back to Battalion

1:05:41.771 --> 1:05:43.064
before they disappear.

1:05:51.238 --> 1:05:52.948
You wanna ask me,
don't you?

1:05:53.032 --> 1:05:54.450
Ask you what, sir?

1:05:54.533 --> 1:05:56.786
You wanna know
if they're true or not,
the stories about me.

1:05:58.537 --> 1:06:00.164
Did you ever notice
with stories like that,

1:06:00.247 --> 1:06:02.875
everyone says they heard it
from someone who was there,

1:06:02.958 --> 1:06:04.710
but then when
you ask that person,

1:06:04.794 --> 1:06:07.171
they say they heard it
from someone who was there.

1:06:08.714 --> 1:06:09.799
It's nothing new, really.

1:06:09.882 --> 1:06:11.967
I bet if you went
back 2,000 years,

1:06:12.051 --> 1:06:13.719
you'd hear a couple
of centurions standing around

1:06:13.803 --> 1:06:16.389
and yakking about how
Tercius lopped off the heads

1:06:16.472 --> 1:06:18.140
of some
Carthaginian prisoners.

1:06:19.684 --> 1:06:22.311
Well, maybe they
kept talking about it

1:06:22.395 --> 1:06:24.522
because they never heard
Tercius deny it.

1:06:26.524 --> 1:06:28.693
Well, maybe that's
because Tercius

1:06:28.776 --> 1:06:29.985
knew there was some
value to the men

1:06:30.069 --> 1:06:31.821
thinking he was the meanest,
toughest son of a bitch

1:06:31.904 --> 1:06:33.072
in the whole
Roman Legion.

1:06:35.658 --> 1:06:36.784
Sir?

1:06:39.120 --> 1:06:42.123
These men aren't really
concerned about the stories.

1:06:42.206 --> 1:06:44.417
They're just glad
to have you as our C.O.

1:06:45.710 --> 1:06:48.045
They're happy to have
a good leader again.

1:06:48.129 --> 1:06:51.382
Well, from what I've heard,
they've always had one.

1:06:51.465 --> 1:06:53.884
I've been told there's
always been one man
they could count on.

1:06:55.678 --> 1:06:57.263
Led 'em into
the Bois Jacques,

1:06:57.346 --> 1:07:00.182
held them together when
they had the crap shelled
out of 'em In the woods.

1:07:00.266 --> 1:07:02.268
Every day he kept
the spirits up,

1:07:02.351 --> 1:07:04.854
kept the men focused,
gave 'em direction.

1:07:04.937 --> 1:07:07.231
All the things
a good combat leader does.

1:07:13.487 --> 1:07:15.740
You don't have any idea
who I'm talking about, do you?

1:07:16.991 --> 1:07:17.908
No, sir.

1:07:17.992 --> 1:07:19.785
Hell, it was you,
1st Sergeant.

1:07:21.036 --> 1:07:22.246
Ever since Winters
made Battalion,

1:07:22.329 --> 1:07:23.873
you've been
the leader of Easy Company.

1:07:30.379 --> 1:07:32.798
Oh...

1:07:32.882 --> 1:07:36.093
And you're not gonna be
1st Sergeant.much longer,

1:07:36.177 --> 1:07:37.595
Sir?

1:07:39.305 --> 1:07:41.223
Winters put in
for a battlefield commission,

1:07:41.307 --> 1:07:42.892
and Sink approved
on your behalf.

1:07:42.975 --> 1:07:45.478
You should get
the official nod
in a few days.

1:07:49.023 --> 1:07:51.066
Congratulations,
Lieutenant.

1:08:04.330 --> 1:08:08.292
♪ ♪

1:08:14.548 --> 1:08:16.967
Hey, look,
it's 1st Battalion.

1:08:17.051 --> 1:08:19.553
Hey! Hey!

1:08:17.051 --> 1:08:19.553
Man: What do you want?

1:08:19.637 --> 1:08:22.890
Yeah, thanks for crapping
in our foxholes,
you shitheads.

1:08:22.973 --> 1:08:24.308
Hey, it's our pleasure.

1:08:24.391 --> 1:08:27.019
Luz: Yeah.

1:08:24.391 --> 1:08:27.019
Enjoy the walk, boys.

1:08:30.940 --> 1:08:32.399
(lighter clinks, flicks)

